# Dependency Visibility Rules

Use this rule when creating or updating issues and when planning work order.

## Core Rule

Dependencies between issues must be visible in the issue (e.g. “Depends on #N”) and, if applicable, on the project board. Do not start an issue whose dependencies are not closed or removed.

## Make Dependencies Explicit

In the issue body, call out:

- **Depends on #N** — List issue numbers that must be merged (or removed as dependency) before this issue can be started.
- Why the dependency exists — e.g. “Requires auth API” or “Requires ParseExerciseSkill output shape.”

## GymVoice Dependency Patterns

Many features depend on earlier work. Examples:

- Voice logging depends on auth and session start/API.
- Superset/triset grouping depends on single-set parsing and persistence.
- History view depends on session/set persistence.
- Any issue that touches VoiceParserAgent, ParseExerciseSkill, GroupSeriesSkill, or persistence should list any issue that must merge first (e.g. backend models/routes, voice API integration).

Respect milestone order (M1 before M2). If the issue consumes data or API from another issue, that other issue is a dependency.

## Do Not

- Start an issue when a dependency is still open unless the dependency was explicitly removed or deferred.
- Assume “someone else will do the base work”; make it explicit.

## Final Rule

If the implementer cannot tell what must be done first, dependencies are not visible enough. Reference: MILESTONES.md, MVP_PLAN.md, TASK_EXECUTION_WORKFLOW.md.
